<tr><td class="printline">
<span class="postbody">I use Firefox or Mozilla. I downloaded Firefox at work simply cause I only needed a web browser there and it's a much smaller download than Mozilla. I hate IE and how full of security holes it's full of. Most of the security flaws can be traced to Microsoft's "enhancements" to IE as well as Windows. 
<br />

<br />
As for firewalls. I recommend Zone Alarm. It is well within the price range of 100% of users already on the internet. Free. It's not the best and I know others have their own preferences but I think it's one of the better firewalls around. Especially in it's price range. It's definitely better than Windows XP's built in firewall. Although in defense of XP's firewall, a cheezy firewall is better than none.
<br />

<br />
I use Norton Utilities for general system maintenance as well as for anti-virus. Making sure your virus definitions are up to date and run a regularly scheduled full scan (once every 2-4 weeks is fine). You don't use your computer 24/7 so just pick a night where you're not using it and have it running with your monitor off. Wake up in the morning and finish the scan in case it finds a virus or something.
<br />

<br />
Also use Norton (or some other program) and defragment your hard drive. Because of the way computers write and delete programs and files, your files and applications are most likely not written in a single continuous line. It's broken up into fragments which the computer has to search for when you access that file. This means that your hard drive receives a serious thrashing when searching for files on a highly fragmented hard drive.  If your files were all written on a single continuous line then the hard drive would only need to search for the file once and then read the whole thing instead of doing multiple searches across the hard drive. The problem gets progressively worse the more you use your hard drive. Degragmenting your hard drive can help a lot with speeding up your computer, especially when running a game like everquest that accesses the hard drive a lot.
<br />

<br />
Next up, you want to run something to get rid of spyware on your system. Spybot or Ad-Aware are good. I personally use Ad-Aware. Running this means that browser hijacks that makes popups come up on your browser even on a web site that has no popups will be squashed. Not to mention the darn spyware that collects information (some of it very private) on your computer usage and habits.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
</td></tr>
<br />
